                        </big></big></big>
                <p style="color: rgb(102, 0, 0);"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                       size="-1"><big><big><big><strong>D&amp;C 59:9-13</strong></big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 40px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                   size="-1"><big><big><big> 8 Thou shalt offer a sacrifice unto the Lord
                                        thy God in righteousness, even that of a broken heart and a contrite
                                        spirit.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 40px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                   size="-1"><big><big><big>9 And that thou mayest more fully keep
                                        thyself unspotted from the world, thou shalt go to the house of prayer
                                        and offer up thy sacraments upon my holy day;</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 40px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                   size="-1"><big><big><big>10 For verily this is a day appointed unto
                                        you to rest from your labors, and to pay thy devotions unto the Most
                                        High;</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 40px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                   size="-1"><big><big><big>11 Nevertheless thy vows shall be offered up
                                        in righteousness on all days and at all times;</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 40px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                   size="-1"><big><big><big>12 But remember that on this, the Lord's day,
                                        thou shalt offer thine oblations and thy sacraments unto the Most High,
                                        confessing thy sins unto thy brethren, and before the
                                        Lord.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 40px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                   size="-1"><big><big><big>13 And on this day thou shalt do none other
                                        thing, only let thy food be prepared with singleness of heart that thy
                                        fasting may be perfect, or, in other words, that thy joy may
                                        be full.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><big style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);"><big><big><font
                                    face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><strong>Relating to D&amp;C 59</strong></big></big></big></font></big></big></big></div>
                <p style="margin-left: 80px; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"><big><big><big><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><strong>Latin Meanings</strong></big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Sacer</em> </strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big>(root word for sacrifice and
                                        sacrament): Latin adj. sacred, holy, dedicated to a divinity,
                                        pertaining to religious or divine issues. </big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Sacrifice</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big>: Latin noun<em> sacrificium</em>,
                                        the noun <em>sacrifice</em>, from the verb <em>sacrificare</em>, from
                                        sacer, <em>sacred, + -ficium, deed</em>, from the verb facere, <em>do</em>
                                        or <em>make</em>. </big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Sacrament:</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><em></em> From Latin noun <em>sacramentum</em>,
                                        from the verb <em>sacrare </em>("hallow, consecrate"), from adjective
                                        <em>sacer</em> ("sacred"), + suffix -<em>mentum</em>.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <div style="margin-left: 80px; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"><big><big><big><font
                                    face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><strong>1828 NOAH WEBSTER
                                                DICTIONARY</strong></big></big></big></font></big></big></big></div>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Sacrifice</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big>: 1. To offer to God in homage
                                        or worship, by killing and consuming, as victims on an altar; to
                                        immolate, either as an atonement for sin, or to procure favor, or to
                                        express thankfulness; as, to sacrifice an ox or a lamb. 2. To destroy,
                                        surrender or suffer to be lost for the sake of obtaining something; as,
                                        to sacrifice the peace of the
                                        church to a little vain curiosity. 3. To devote with loss. 4. To
                                        destroy; to kill.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Righteousness</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big>: Purity of heart and rectitude
                                        of life; conformity of heart and life to the divine law. Righteousness,
                                        as used in Scripture and theology, in which it is chiefly
                                        used, is nearly equivalent to holiness, comprehending holy principles
                                        and affections of heart, and conformity of life to the divine law. It
                                        includes all we call justice, honesty
                                        and virtue, with holy affections; in short, it is true religion.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Broken Heart:</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><em></em> Having the spirits
                                        depressed or crushed by grief or despair.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Contrite</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><em></em>: to break or bruise;
                                        to rub or wear. Literally, worn or bruised. Hence, broken-hearted for
                                        sin; deeply affected with grief and sorrow for having offended God;
                                        humble; penitent; as a contrite sinner.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Spirit:</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><em></em> 4. Temper; disposition
                                        of mind, habitual or temporary; as a man of a generous spirit, or of a
                                        revengeful spirit; the ornament of a meek and quiet spirit. Let us go
                                        to
                                        the house of God in the spirit of prayer. 5. The soul of man; the
                                        intelligent, immaterial and immortal part of human beings. ... 8. Turn
                                        of mind; temper; occasions; state of the
                                        mind. 9. Powers of mind distinct from the body.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Sacraments:</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><em></em> In present usage, an
                                        outward and visible sign of inward and spiritual grace; or more
                                        particularly, a solemn religious ceremony enjoined by Christ, the head
                                        of
                                        the christian church, to be observed by his followers, by which their
                                        special relation to him is created, or their obligations to him renewed
                                        and ratified. Thus baptism is called
                                        a sacrament, for by it persons are separated from the world, brought
                                        into Christ's visible church, and laid under particular obligations to
                                        obey his precepts. The eucharist or
                                        communion of the Lord's supper, is also a sacrament, for by
                                        commemorating the death and dying love of Christ, christians avow their
                                        special relation to him, and renew
                                        their obligations to be faithful to their divine Master. When we use
                                        sacrament without any qualifying word, we mean by it the eucharist or
                                        Lord's supper. </big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Devotions</em>:</strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big> 1. The state of being
                                        dedicated, consecrated, or solemnly set apart for a particular purpose.
                                        2. A solemn attention to the Supreme Being in worship; a yielding
                                        of the heart and affections to God, with reverence, faith and piety, in
                                        religious duties, particularly in prayer and meditation; devoutness. 3.
                                        External worship; acts of religion;
                                        performance of religious duties.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Vows</em>:</strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big> A solemn promise made to God. </big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Offer up</em>:</strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big> 1. Literally, to bring to or
                                        before; hence, to present for acceptance or rejection; to exhibit
                                        something that may be taken or received or not. ... 3. To present, as
                                        an
                                        act of worship; to immolate; to sacrifice; often with up.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Oblations</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big><em></em>: Any thing offered or
                                        presented in worship or sacred service; an offering; a sacrifice.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Fast[ing]</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big>: 1. To abstain from food,
                                        beyond the usual time; to omit to take the usual meals, for a time; as,
                                        to fast a day or a week. 2. To abstain from food voluntarily, for the
                                        mortification of the body or appetites, or as a token of grief, sorrow
                                        and affliction.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <p style="margin-left: 120px;"><big><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong><em>Perfect</em></strong></big></big></big></font><font
                                face="Arial" size="-1"><big><big><big>: Finished; complete;
                                        consummate; not defective; having all that is requisite to its nature
                                        and kind; as a perfect statue; a perfect likeness; a perfect work; a
                                        perfect
                                        system.</big></big></big></font></big></big></big></p>
                <br>
                <big style="color: rgb(102, 0, 0);"><big><big><font face="Arial"
                                                                    size="-1"><big><big><big><strong>1 Cor 11:23-30</strong></big></big></big></font></big></big></big>
